#### CHAPTER XVI

#### ASTROLOGY

<span id="an_16_1">1</span>. Thorndike, II, 973, IV, 317; Maimonides,
*Mishneh Torah*, *‘Akkum*, 11, 8; *Nishmat Ḥayim*, III, 21; Moses of
Tachau lent his support to this Maimonidean position in his
anti-Maimonidean polemic (*Oẓar Neḥmad*, III, 82), and severely
criticized "those men to whom the spirit of *Torah* is foreign, who busy
themselves with astrology and believe in it and make it their creed, and
thereby bring harm to others." See *JE*, II, 243 ff. and *EJ*, III, 578
ff., for a general survey of the rabbinic material. The use of the word
*mazal*, "star," "constellation," to signify "luck" may be seen in the
Talmud; in the Middle Ages it was more frequent. "We call good fortune,
good *mazal*, and the reverse, bad *mazal* . . . in German it is *Glück*
and in Italian *ventura*" (Levita, *Tishbi*, s. v. *mazal*). This usage
of the word did not displace its astrological sense in the vernacular
until modern times.

